@Node "NETCALLCFG" "NetCall_English.guide/NETCALLCFG"
@Next "TRAPDOORCFG"
@Toc "CONFIG"

The configuration-file NetCall.cfg
==================================

   @{b}NetCall@{ub} will look for its configuration-file in the following
directories:

  1. Mail: (if assigned)

  2. The current directory

  3. The directory, where the environment-variable @{i}NETCALLCONFIG@{ui} points
     to

  4. Shell-argument @{i}CONFIG@{ui} (See also @{"Execution from a shell" Link "SHELL"}.)


   The configuration-file of @{b}NetCall@{ub} may/must include the following
parameters:

@{b}OUTBOUND "@{i}Path@{ui}"@{ub}
     @{i}OUTBOUND@{ui}-directory of your mailer (example: @{b}Mail:Outbound@{ub}).

@{b}NODELIST "@{i}Path@{ui}"@{ub}
     Directory where your nodelist can be found (example:
     @{b}Mail:Nodelist@{ub}). If you  don't have a nodelist, delete this
     line from your configuration-file or mark  it out as a comment.

@{b}MAILER "@{i}Path/Mailer@{ui}"@{ub}
     TrapDoor-mailer (example: @{b}Mail:Bin/TrapDoor@{ub}).

@{b}TRAPTELL "@{i}Path/TrapTell@{ui}"@{ub}
     If you want @{b}NetCall@{ub} to start @{i}TrapDoor@{ui} not as a shell-command, but
     to control @{i}TrapDoor@{ui} via then @{i}TrapTell@{ui}-command, you must specify
     the @{i}TrapTell@{ui}-command here. To enable the tell-function, you have
     to specify  @{i}TELL@{ui} as a shell-argument to @{b}NetCall@{ub}. See also
     @{"Execution from shell" Link "SHELL"}.

@{b}ARGAPPEND "@{i}Mailer shell-arguments@{ui}"@{ub}
     Arguments specified here, will be passed to the mailer, directly.
     To work probably  @{b}NetCall@{ub} and not @{i}TrapDoor@{ui} should be responsible
     for the retries. This  can either be achieved by writing @{b}RETRIES 0@{ub}
     in your @{b}TrapDoor.cfg@{ub} or  passing @{b}RETRIES 0@{ub} here as a
     shell-argument to the mailer.   See also @{"Configuration of TrapDoor" Link "TRAPDOORCFG"}.

     (example: @{b}RETRIES 0@{ub}).

@{b}ARGAPPENDICONIFIED "@{i}Mailer shell-Arguments@{ui}"@{ub}
     Additional shell-arguments passed to the mailer, when @{b}NetCall@{ub}
     operates  in the iconified mode (example: @{b}QUIET@{ub} would cause
     @{i}TrapDoor@{ui} to open no  windows, when @{b}NetCall@{ub} is iconified).

@{b}TDLOGFILE "@{i}Path/TrapDoor-LogFile@{ui}"@{ub}
     LogFile of TrapDoor (example: @{b}Mail:Logs/TrapDoor.log@{ub}).

@{b}NETCALLSTART "@{i}Shell-command@{ui}"@{ub}
     This shell-command gets executed at @{b}NetCall@{ub}'s startup.

@{b}NETCALLEND "@{i}Shell-command@{ui}"@{ub}
     This shell-command gets executed at @{b}NetCall@{ub}'s shutdown.

@{b}AFTERSESSION "@{i}Shell-command@{ui}"@{ub}
     This shell-command gets executed after each poll.

@{b}HELPCOMMAND "@{i}Shell-command@{ui}"@{ub}
     This shell-command gets executed if you press the <@{i}HELP@{ui}>-key when
     the  @{b}NetCall@{ub}-window is active.

     (@{b}SYS:Utilities/AmigaGuide HELP:english/NetCall.guide PUBSCREEN
     NETCALL@{ub}).

@{b}STARTUPDELAY @{i}seconds@{ui}@{ub}
     Time that should delay before @{b}NetCall@{ub} starts the poll-process.
     This delay  allows you to deselect unwanted list-entries. This
     option is only active when  @{i}ALLACTIVE@{ui} is given as a
     shell-argument. (@{b}STARTUPDELAY 0@{ub} means no  delay).

@{b}REDIALDELAY @{i}seconds@{ui}@{ub}
     Time that should delay if all lines are @{i}BUSY@{ui} at the end of the
     poll-list.

@{b}REDIALDELAYENTRY @{i}seconds@{ui}@{ub}
     Time that should delay after each entry in the poll-list. This
     option is useful  for modems with redial-restrictions.

@{b}MAXRETRIES @{i}retries@{ui}@{ub}
     After having reached this amount of retries, @{b}NetCall@{ub} will
     automatically  deactivate all active list-entries. (Use @{b}MAXRETRIES
     0@{ub}, if you don't want  automatical deactivation).

@{b}MAXRETRIESCOMMAND "@{i}Shell-command@{ui}"@{ub}
     This AmigaDOS-command gets executed, if the amount of @{i}MAXRETRIES@{ui} is
     expired.

     (example: @{b}rexx:rx 'address NETCALL QUIT'@{ub})

     (This example sends the ARexx-command @{i}QUIT@{ui} to @{b}NetCall@{ub}. This will
     quit @{b}NetCall@{ub}.)

     If @{i}MAXRETRIESCOMMAND@{ui} is not specified, @{b}NetCall@{ub} will deselect all
     entries in the poll-list.

@{b}MULTILINE@{ub}
     This keyword will cause @{b}NetCall@{ub} to search for other nodes of your
     destination system(s) in the nodelist. The search will be
     performed by a second  task, so no delay of the polling-task
     should be noticeable. Use @{i}NOMULTILINE@{ui}  if you don't want this
     option.

@{b}AUTOQUIT@{ub}
     @{b}NetCall@{ub} will be automatically terminated as soon as all jobs are
     processed.   Use @{i}NOAUTOQUIT@{ui} if you don't want this option.

@{b}MAILERABORT @{i}(ABORTNETCALL|CONTINUE|REQUEST)@{ui}@{ub}
     If you quit your mailer (user-break, <@{i}ESC@{ui}>), @{b}NetCall@{ub} may:

        @{b}*@{ub} be quitted, too           (@{i}MAILERABORT ABORTNETCALL@{ui})

        @{b}*@{ub} poll at the next node     (@{i}MAILERABORT CONTINUE@{ui})

        @{b}*@{ub} open a requester          (@{i}MAILERABORT REQUEST@{ui})

@{b}SAVELASTPOLLDATE@{ub}
     If this option is enabled, @{b}NetCall@{ub} will display the date of the
     last  successful call to each of your bosses in the
     listview-gadget. @{b}NetCall@{ub}  will store the needed data in a file
     called @{b}NetCall.polldates@{ub}, which  can be located in your @{b}Mail:@{ub}- or
     in the current directory at  @{b}NetCall@{ub}'s startup.
     (@{i}NOSAVELASTPOLLDATE@{ui} if you don't want this option).

@{b}OPENPUBSCREEN @{i}"Screenname" Width Height Depth ScreenModeID@{ui}@{ub}
     Force @{b}NetCall@{ub} to open its own public-screen. All values must be
     given  in decimal format. To specifiy the @{i}ScreenModeID@{ui}, you may
     use the  @{i}ScreenModeViewer@{ui}-Utility (example: @{b}NETCALL 640 256 2
     167936@{ub}).

@{b}PUBSCREEN "@{i}Screenname@{ui}"@{ub}
     Open @{b}NetCall@{ub} on this public-screen. If @{b}NetCall@{ub} can't find this
     screen to open on, @{b}NetCall@{ub} will open its window on your workbench.
     If you wish @{b}NetCall@{ub} to open its own public-screen (@{i}OPENPUBSCREEN@{ui})
     you  must specifiy the same name at @{i}OPENPUBSCREEN@{ui} and @{i}PUBSCREEN@{ui}
     (example: @{b}NETCALL@{ub}):

@{b}SCREENTOFRONT@{ub}
     If @{i}SCREENTOFRONT@{ui} is specified, @{b}NetCall@{ub} will automatically bring
     the screen where the @{b}NetCall@{ub}-window is opened to the front.
     (@{i}NOSCREENTOFRONT@{ui} if not desired).

@{b}BACKDROPWINDOW@{ub}
     @{b}NetCall@{ub} can optionally open an invinsible backdrop-window on its
     own  public-screen. If you enable this option, you are able to
     select @{b}NetCall@{ub}'s  menu even if you clicked outside the @{b}NetCall@{ub}
     main-window. This option becomes  only active, if @{b}NetCall@{ub} opens
     its own public-screen. Opening a backdrop-window  does @{i}not@{ui} need
     any memory, but it could slow down window-refreshing  (esp. if
     many windows are open). Use @{i}NOBACKDROPWINDOW@{ui} if you don't want  a
     backdrop-window.

@{b}PUBSCREENMAILER "@{i}Screenname@{ui}"@{ub}
     You can optionally force the mailer to open its windows on this
     public-screen  (example: @{b}Workbench@{ub}).

@{b}WINDOW @{i}X/Y/Width/Height@{ui}@{ub}
     Window-position/-size (big @{b}NetCall@{ub}-window, incl. list-view-gadgets
     and  text-gadget) (example: @{b}30/30/400/180@{ub}).

@{b}WINDOWZOOM @{i}X/Y/Width/Height@{ui}@{ub}
     Window-position/-size of the zoomed (little) @{b}NetCall@{ub}-window. If you
     specifiy @{i}AUTO@{ui} rather than a decimal value as the height, @{b}NetCall@{ub}
     will  automatically adapt its window-height to your actual
     font-size  (example: @{b}30/30/400/AUTO@{ub}).

@{b}WINDOWFILEREQ @{i}X/Y/Width/Height@{ui}@{ub}
     Position/size of the REQ-file editor window.

     (example: @{b}50/40/190/240@{ub}).

@{b}WINDOWFILEREQZOOM @{i}X/Y/Width/Height@{ui}@{ub}
     Position/size of the REQ-file editor window in zoomed state.

     (example: @{b}50/40/200/100@{ub}).

@{b}WINDOWTOOLBOX @{i}X/Y/Width/Height@{ui}@{ub}
     Position/size of the toolbox. @{b}NetCall@{ub} will ignore the @{i}Width@{ui} value
     and adapt the window-width to the actual screenfont and to the
     gadgets.

     (example: @{b}50/40/0/100@{ub}).

@{b}WINDOWACTIVATE@{ub}
     Activate the @{b}NetCall@{ub}-window when opened (use @{i}NOWINDOWACTIVATE@{ui} if
     you  don't want to activate).

@{b}WINDOWFONTNAME "@{i}Fontname@{ui}"@{ub}
     The Font that should be used for the list-view-gadgets (example:
     @{b}topaz.font@{ub}).

@{b}WINDOWFONTSIZE @{i}Height@{ui}@{ub}
     Font-size used for the list-view-gadgets (example: @{b}8@{ub}).

@{b}LVITEMHEIGHT @{i}Pixel@{ui}@{ub}
     Space between the list-view-entries (given in pixel) (example: @{b}1@{ub}).

@{b}OPENBIG@{ub}
     If you specify @{i}OPENBIG@{ui}, @{b}NetCall@{ub} will always open its big window,
     no care if there are file-requests or crash-mails in your
     @{i}OUTBOUND@{ui}-directory.   Use @{i}NOOPENBIG@{ui} if you don't want this
     option.

@{b}SEARCHOPTS @{i}5/6@{ui}@{ub}
     Search-options (for @{i}MULTILINE@{ui}). Leave it be...

@{b}SEARCHPATTERN "@{i}Pattern@{ui}"@{ub}
     Pick up all nodes with this fido-flags to the ToDo-list. A valid
     AmigaDOS pattern  can be given here. If you specify @{b}~(#?ISDN#?)@{ub}
     @{b}NetCall@{ub} will pick up all  fido-nodes without @{i}ISDN@{ui}. If you don't
     specify @{i}MULTILINE@{ui}, this keyword  will have no effect.

@{b}SUPRESSREQ @{i}"TrapDoor error"@{ui}@{ub}
     @{b}NetCall@{ub} may supress/terminate some of its error-requesters
     automatically.   You may specify any amount of @{i}SUPRESSREQ@{ui}-commands
     here. (Note the "#?...#?").   (example: @{b}"#?NO CARRIER#?"@{ub}).

@{b}COMMAND @{i}"Name of the menu-entry" "Shell-command" ASYNC GADGET GAP@{ui}@{ub}
     With this keyword you are abled to define your own menu-entries in
     the  @{b}NetCall@{ub}-menustrip. You may specify any number of
     @{i}COMMAND@{ui}-keywords here.   If you add @{i}ASYNC@{ui}, @{b}NetCall@{ub} will launch
     the command as an seperate process.   (example: @{b}Test1
     SYS:Prefs/Time@{ub}).

     If you want this entry appear in the toolbox, you have to append
     @{i}GADGET@{ui}.   You can insert a gap after the gadget if you specify @{i}GAP@{ui}.
     (example: @{b}Test1 SYS:Prefs/Time GADGET GAP@{ub}).

     If you want to send ARexx-commands to @{b}NetCall@{ub} itself, you have to
     use  the @{i}ASYNC@{ui}-flag. Otherwise this will cause a deadlock of
     @{b}NetCall@{ub}.   (@{b}NetCall@{ub} would wait until the ARexx-command is
     finished, but the handling  of the command can't start while
     @{b}NetCall@{ub} is waiting).   (example: @{b}"Quit NetCall" "rexx:rx 'address
     NETCALL QUIT'" ASYNC GADGET@{ub}).

@{b}BOSS @{i}ID(*)  Node/Phone  MyAddr  Password  Retries  BeforeSession  AfterSession@{ui}@{ub}
     With the @{i}BOSS@{ui}-keyword you can define all lines of your own
     fido-bosses. You may  specify any number of @{i}BOSS@{ui}-keywords. By
     using several different @{i}IDs@{ui} you  can configure your system for
     multi-bossing. Entries with a * behind the @{i}ID@{ui}  will be displayed
     in the @{b}NetCall@{ub}-window (list-view-gadget). You may use  different
     amounts of @{i}retries@{ui} for each line of your boss (optional). If the
     line is BUSY, @{b}NetCall@{ub} will automatically retry this line (if
     @{i}retries@{ui}  is specified). You can specify phone-numbers rather than
     node-numbers if your boss  has unlisted lines. @{i}BeforeSession@{ui} and
     @{i}AfterSession@{ui} can be scripts,  which will be executed before and
     after the mailer-call to the corresponding  @{i}BOSS@{ui} (optional).

     Example:

           BOSS  SO*   2:246/2248   2:246/2248.20  test  3  Export  Import
           BOSS  SO    2:246/2249   2:246/2248.20  test
           BOSS  CDS*  2:246/1045   2:246/1045.11  test  0  Export  Import
           BOSS  CDS   2:246/1046   2:246/1045.11  test
           BOSS  CDS   2:246/1047   2:246/1045.11  test  3
           BOSS  CDS   07131167890  2:246/1045.11  test

@{b}CALL @{i}ID(*)  Node/Phone  MyAddr  Password@{ui}@{ub}
     The @{i}CALL@{ui}-directive can be used to add fido-nodes to @{b}NetCall@{ub}'s
     ToDo-list, which are no personal bosses. This might be useful if
     you call a  system regularly, to receive data put on hold for you.
     The password is optional.

     Example:

           CALL  ID1*  2:246/1234   2:246/1045.11  test
           CALL  ID2*  2:246/5678   2:246/1045.11

@{b}ADDNODE @{i}NODE ADDNODE...@{ui}@{ub}
     With the @{i}ADDNODE@{ui}-variable you can specify additional node- or
     phone-numbers  of nodes which are currently in @{b}NetCall@{ub}'s list.
     This might be useful to  call lines which are unlisted in the
     nodelist. Please notice that this additional  nodes/phonenumbers
     are not displayed in the upper list-view-gadget. They  are only
     displayed when their @{i}NODE@{ui}-entry is selected.

     Example:

           ADDNODE 2:246/1045 07131/123456 07131/987654
           ADDNODE 2:246/2248 07141/123456


@EndNode

@Node "TRAPDOORCFG" "NetCall_English.guide/TRAPDOORCFG"
@Next "USESPOT"
@Prev "NETCALLCFG"
@Toc "CONFIG"

The configuration of TrapDoor
=============================

   You should set the amount of @{i}RETRIES@{ui} in your @{b}TrapDoor.cfg@{ub} to 0
(@{b}RETRIES 0@{ub}), because @{b}NetCall@{ub} will do this from now on.

   @{b}NetCall@{ub} will call each line of the desired destination-system, if the
other lines are @{i}BUSY@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "USESPOT" "NetCall_English.guide/USESPOT"
@Next "USEUMS"
@Prev "TRAPDOORCFG"
@Toc "CONFIG"

The usage of NetCall with Spot
==============================

   To use @{b}NetCall@{ub} with @{i}Spot@{ui} (1)  as optimized as possible, you should
configure @{i}Spot@{ui}  as follows:

   Execute @{b}NetCall@{ub} @{i}only@{ui} from your first boss-entry in the
@{i}Spot@{ui}-configuration (Settings -> System...). Enable the
@{i}asynchronous@{ui}-button.

      NetCall >NIL: OPENBIG

   All other @{i}NetCall@{ui}-entries of @{i}Spot@{ui} should be cleared.

   If you press the @{i}NetCall@{ui}-button of @{i}Spot@{ui}, @{b}NetCall@{ub} will be started.

   If you have multiple bosses, @{i}Spot@{ui} will no longer ask you where to
poll.   You can choose this directly in the @{b}NetCall@{ub}-window.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  @{i}Spot@{ui} is copyright (C)  Nico François


@EndNode

@Node "USEUMS" "NetCall_English.guide/USEUMS"
@Next "MAILMGR"
@Prev "USESPOT"
@Toc "CONFIG"

The usage of NetCall with UMS
=============================

   If you want to use @{b}NetCall@{ub} with @{i}UMS@{ui} (1)  you don't have to change
anything in  your @{b}ums.config@{ub}.

   @{b}NetCall@{ub} can easily be started by double-clicking its icon on the
workbench  or executing it in a shell.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  @{i}UMS@{ui} is copyright  (C) Martin Horneffer


@EndNode

@Node "MAILMGR" "NetCall_English.guide/MAILMGR"
@Prev "USEUMS"
@Toc "CONFIG"

The usage of NetCall with MailManager
=====================================

   Just like at the usage of @{b}NetCall@{ub} with @{i}UMS@{ui}, you have to change
nothing  in your configuration of @{i}MailManager@{ui} (1)  if you want to use
@{b}NetCall@{ub} with  @{i}MailManager@{ui}. See also @{"The usage of NetCall with UMS" Link "USEUMS"}.

   @{b}NetCall@{ub} can easily be started by double-clicking its icon on the
workbench  or executing it in a shell.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  @{i}MailManager@{ui} is copyright  (C) Pino Aliberti


@EndNode

@Node "AREXX" "NetCall_English.guide/AREXX"
@Next "AUTHOR"
@Prev "GUI"
@Toc "Main"

ARexx-interface
***************

   The ARexx-interface of @{b}NetCall@{ub} can be reached via the public port
@{i}NETCALL@{ui}.

   The interface knows the following commands:

@{b}ABORTDELAY@{ub}
     abort the actual delay-loop (if there is one).

@{b}ABORTMAILER@{ub}
     cancels the mailer, if he is currently active. If @{b}NetCall@{ub} is in a
     delay-loop,  this loop will be canceled, too.

@{b}BEEP@{ub}
     flashes the screen of @{b}NetCall@{ub}.

@{b}DESELECTALL@{ub}
     deselects all the active entries in the list-view-gadget. The
     poll-process of  the active entry will not be stopped. (like the
     menu-item 'deselect all').

@{b}HELP@{ub}
     call the help-function of @{b}NetCall@{ub} (just like the 'help' menu-item).

@{b}ICONIFY@{ub}
     iconifies @{b}NetCall@{ub}.

@{b}ISICONIFIED@{ub}
     returns @{i}warn@{ui} (5) if the user-interface of @{b}NetCall@{ub} is currently
     open or  @{i}ok@{ui} (0) if @{b}NetCall@{ub} is iconified.

@{b}NETCALL2FRONT@{ub}
     brings the screen of @{b}NetCall@{ub} to the front.

@{b}NODEMANUAL @{i}NODE,ACTIVE/S@{ui}@{ub}
     Adds a node to @{b}NetCall@{ub}'s poll-list. The poll-process will be
     started, if you  specify @{i}ACTIVE@{ui}.

     Example: @{b}NODEMANUAL 2:246/1045 ACTIVE@{ub}

     When no parameter ist specified, @{b}NetCall@{ub} will open the 'add node
     manual'-window.

@{b}QUIT@{ub}
     terminates @{b}NetCall@{ub}. The poll-process will be terminated, too.

@{b}REQUESTFILE@{ub}
     open the file-requester (just like the 'request file...'
     menu-item). This command  has no effect when @{b}NetCall@{ub} is in
     @{i}ICONIFY@{ui}-mode.

@{b}SELECTALL@{ub}
     selects all the entries in the list-view-gadget. This may start
     the poll-process  (like the menu-item 'select all').

@{b}UNICONIFY@{ub}
     opens @{b}NetCall@{ub} after @{i}ICONIFY@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "GUI" "NetCall_English.guide/GUI"
@Next "AREXX"
@Prev "CONFIG"
@Toc "Main"

User-interface
**************

   The mainwindow of @{b}NetCall@{ub} displays two list-view-gadgets and one
text-gadget.

   All nodes, which should be called are displayed in the upper
list-view-gadget.  This are the nodes from your @{i}BOSS@{ui}-entries (marked
with an '*'), the nodes from your @{i}CALL@{ui}-entries and eventually nodes
where you want to crash mails to or where you want to request files.

   You can select those entries by clicking on them with the mouse or
pressing one of the function-keys (F1-F10). Selected nodes appear in
the lower list-view-gadget.

   Selected entries are displayed with all their lines (if they do have
more than one line, of course). You can deselect individual entries by
clicking on them with the mouse.

   The entries in the list-view-gadgets have the following meaning:

     CRP *> 2:246/1045  (CDS Port #1)
     
     C : Crashmail ready for this node
     R : File-request waiting for this node
     P : This node waits to be polled (f.e. your boss)
     * : This entry is selected
     > : This entry is actually active, in other words: your mailer calls
         this node right now

   The text-gadget displays actual information of the program.


@EndNode

